answers.body_markdown:
It is impossible to create either a `UserServiceImpl` or a `SecurityConfiguration` object without having already created the other:

* To create a `UserServiceImpl` Spring needs to call its constructor `UserServiceImpl(UserRepository userRepository, PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder)` which it can only do after it has created a `PasswordEncoder` object.

* To create a `PasswordEncoder` object Spring has to call `SecurityConfiguration.passwordEncoder()` which it can only do after it has created a `SecurityConfiguration` object.

* To create a `SecurityConfiguration` Spring needs to call its constructor `SecurityConfiguration(UserService userService)` which it can only do after it has created a `UserServiceImpl` object.

You can solve this problem by defining both the `PasswordEncoder` and the `UserServiceImpl` as beans in the `SecurityConfiguration`:

    public class SecurityConfiguration {
    
        @Bean
        public UserService userService(UserRepository userRepository, PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder) {
            return new UserServiceImpl(userRepository, passwordEncoder);
        }
    
        @Bean
        public PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder() {
            return new BCryptPasswordEncoder();
        }
    }

